# Cursor Rules  ## General  - Always be concise. - Never explain code unless explicitly asked. - Return only the requested result. - Do not generate examples unless requested. - Do not repeat the user's request. - Do not apologize or add unnecessary text. - Minimize output tokens.  ## Code  - Edit existing code instead of rewriting entire files. - Return only changed functions/classes unless full file is requested. - Never duplicate code. - Reuse existing utilities. - Follow existing project architecture. - Prefer the smallest working solution.  ## Reading files  - Read only files required for the task. - Never scan the whole project unless requested. - Avoid reading generated files. - Ignore build artifacts. - Ignore package-lock.json, yarn.lock, pnpm-lock.yaml. - Ignore node_modules. - Ignore dist. - Ignore build. - Ignore .next. - Ignore out. - Ignore coverage. - Ignore logs. - Ignore vendor. - Ignore cache directories.  ## Searching  - Search only relevant directories. - Stop searching once enough context is found. - Prefer filename search before content search.  ## Writing  - Modify only affected files. - Preserve formatting. - Preserve comments. - Preserve naming style.  ## Responses  - Output code first. - Keep explanations under 5 lines. - Do not include markdown unless requested. - Do not describe obvious changes. - Do not summarize every modification.  ## Performance  - Avoid unnecessary refactoring. - Avoid changing unrelated code. - Avoid generating boilerplate. - Avoid creating helper files unless necessary.  ## Dependencies  - Never install new libraries unless requested. - Prefer built-in APIs. - Minimize external dependencies.  ## Git  - Never modify git history. - Never create commits. - Never change branches.  ## Priority  Correctness > Minimal changes > Performance > Readability.
